<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Standard_deviation">Standar=
d deviation</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Arithmetic_progression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Standard deviation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The standard deviation of any arithmetic progression is
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \sigma =3D|d|{\sqrt {\frac {(n-1)(n+1)}{12}}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>=CF=83<!-- =CF=83 --></mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo stretchy=3D"false">|</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mi>d</mi>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo stretchy=3D"false">|</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <msqrt>
            <mfrac>
              <mrow>
                <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
                <mi>n</mi>
                <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
                <mn>1</mn>
                <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
                <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
                <mi>n</mi>
                <mo>+</mo>
                <mn>1</mn>
                <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
              </mrow>
              <mn>12</mn>
            </mfrac>
          </msqrt>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \sigma =3D|d|=
{\sqrt {\frac {(n-1)(n+1)}{12}}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/cf715826b5dd993fb890360647bf511429732b13" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.838ex; width:24.511ex; height:7.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \s=
igma =3D|d|{\sqrt {\frac {(n-1)(n+1)}{12}}}}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>where <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span cla=
ss=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"=
><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaysty=
le n}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>n</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle n}</annotatio=
n>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/a601995d55609f2d9f5e233e36fbe9ea26011b3b" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.395ex; height:1.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle n}"=
></span> is the number of terms in the progression and <span class=3D"mwe-m=
ath-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline =
mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3=
.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle d}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>d</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle d}</annotatio=
n>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/e85ff03cbe0c7341af6b982e47e9f90d235c66ab" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.216ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle d}"=
></span> is the common difference between terms. The formula is essentially=
 the same as the formula for the standard deviation of a <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_uniform_distribution" title=3D"Discrete uni=
form distribution">discrete uniform distribution</a>, interpreting the arit=
hmetic progression as a set of equally probable outcomes.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Intersections">Intersection=
s</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArithmetic=
_progression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Inte=
rsections"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intersection_(set_theory)" =
title=3D"Intersection (set theory)">intersection</a> of any two doubly infi=
nite arithmetic progressions is either empty or another arithmetic progress=
ion, which can be found using the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Chinese_remainder_theorem" title=3D"Chinese remainder theorem">Chinese rema=
inder theorem</a>. If each pair of progressions in a family of doubly infin=
ite arithmetic progressions have a non-empty intersection, then there exist=
s a number common to all of them; that is, infinite arithmetic progressions=
 form a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helly_family" title=3D"Hel=
ly family">Helly family</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic_progression#cite_note-11">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> However, the intersection of infinitely many infinite arithmeti=
c progressions might be a single number rather than itself being an infinit=
e progression.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Amount_of_arithmetic_subset=
s_of_length_k_of_the_set_{1,...,n}"><span id=3D"Amount_of_arithmetic_subset=
s_of_length_k_of_the_set_.7B1.2C....2Cn.7D"></span>Amount of arithmetic sub=
